## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort Timeout → Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (SYSLIB0006). You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(), timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    // Preferred overload — work can observe cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            System.Runtime.ExceptionServices.ExceptionDispatchInfo
                .Capture(ex.InnerException!).Throw();
            throw; // unreachable
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Work that cooperates with cancellation (preferred)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        // ... do work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Legacy fire-and-forget (work ignores cancellation)
var result2 = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SomeLegacyMethod(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work never checks the token** | Cancellation is *cooperative*. If `work` doesn't call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` or pass the token to I/O APIs, it keeps running even after the timeout fires. The caller gets a `TimeoutException`, but the thread pool thread continues silently. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Distinguish timeout cancellation from external/caller cancellation — use the `when` guard shown above. |
| **Expecting instant termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Insert `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` in loops and between expensive calls. |
| **Blocking synchronous calls (e.g., `Thread.Sleep`)** | Replace with `Task.Delay(ms, token)` or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` — plain `Thread.Sleep` ignores the token. |

---

### If work is truly uncooperative (can't modify it)

Move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only safe way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

---

### Summary of API replacements

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|----------------|--------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` / `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested`, decide to continue |
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(() => ..., token)` |
